# NDM Project Conventions

## Repository Structure
This is a monorepo with the following key areas:

- `services/` — TypeScript microservices (admin, config, db-writer, jobs, reports, support, worker, datamigrator-ui)
- `lib/` — Shared TypeScript libraries (api-handler-lib, auth-lib, jobs-lib, logger-lib)
- `liquibase/` — PostgreSQL database migrations (apply + rollback)
- `ndm-api-tests/` — Go-based API integration tests (Ginkgo/Gomega)
- `app-deployment/` — Infrastructure (Terraform, Ansible, Packer, scripts)
- `upgrade/` — Upgrade automation (Ansible playbooks)

## General Rules
- When modifying a shared library in `lib/`, consider the impact on all consuming services.
- Follow existing patterns in the codebase — do not introduce new conventions without discussion.
- Keep services independently deployable; avoid tight coupling between services.
- All services use TypeScript. Do not introduce JavaScript files.
- Environment-specific configuration goes in environment variables, not hardcoded values.

## Git & PRs
- Commit messages should be descriptive and reference issue/ticket numbers.
- Keep PRs focused — one logical change per PR.
- Ensure CI passes before requesting review.

## Docker & Deployment
- Dockerfiles should use multi-stage builds for smaller images.
- Do not include secrets, tokens, or credentials in Docker images or compose files.
- Use the `ndm-docker-compose/` directory for local development setup.

## Dependencies
- Pin dependency versions in `package.json` (exact versions, not ranges).
- Run security audits (`npm audit`) before adding new dependencies.
- Prefer well-maintained packages with active security patching.
